3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates funding rates every hour using a shared order book that aggregates positions across all connected frontends. The funding mechanism operates independently of individual frontend UIs, with rates determined by the collective premium/discount across the entire network. Payments occur automatically between long and short positions, with the shared liquidity model ensuring consistent execution even during high volatility periods."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","AVAX","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX/USDT on Orderly Network benefits from the substantial liquidity of Avalanche's native token while leveraging the platform's multi-chain accessibility. The pair's large trading volume combined with Orderly's shared order book creates deeper liquidity pools than typical DEX perpetuals, leading to more stable funding rates and reduced slippage for arbitrage positions."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX funding rates on Orderly Network typically range from -0.01% to 0.02% during normal market conditions, with spikes reaching ±0.05% during major Avalanche ecosystem announcements. The 1-hour funding frequency creates more granular rate adjustments compared to 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges. Seasonal patterns show increased funding volatility during subnet launches and AVAX staking reward distributions. Cross-chain arbitrage opportunities emerge when Orderly rates diverge from Binance or OKX due to the DEX's isolated liquidity pools."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The shared order book architecture creates arbitrage potential between different frontend interfaces accessing the same liquidity. Rate discrepancies of 0.005-0.015% frequently occur between Orderly rates and major CEX platforms, particularly during Asian trading hours. Multi-chain compatibility allows traders to capitalize on funding differences across NEAR and Ethereum-based frontends. The platform's lower fees (0.02% maker) make micro-arbitrage strategies viable for positions above $10,000, especially when combined with AVAX's typically stable correlation patterns."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network's dependence on frontend partners introduces counterparty risk beyond the core protocol, as individual frontends may experience downtime or liquidity constraints. The complex multi-chain architecture can create delays in position adjustments during high network congestion on NEAR or Ethereum. Smart contract risks are amplified by the shared order book model, where a single vulnerability could affect all connected frontends simultaneously. Bridge risks exist for traders moving funds between chains, and the relatively newer DEX infrastructure lacks the battle-tested history of major centralized exchanges."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Orderly Network's shared order book affect AVAX funding rates?","answer":"The shared order book aggregates all positions across connected DEX frontends, creating deeper liquidity than individual DEXs. This typically results in more stable funding rates and reduced volatility compared to isolated perpetual pools. However, it also means funding rates reflect the collective sentiment across all frontends rather than individual platform dynamics."},{"question":"Can I access AVAX perpetuals on multiple chains through Orderly?","answer":"Yes, Orderly Network operates across NEAR and EVM-compatible chains, allowing access to the same AVAX/USDT liquidity pool through different frontend interfaces. This multi-chain architecture enables cross-chain arbitrage opportunities but requires careful consideration of bridge risks and transaction costs when moving between networks."},{"question":"What makes AVAX funding arbitrage different on a DEX versus CEX?","answer":"DEX funding arbitrage on Orderly involves lower counterparty risk but higher smart contract risk. The 1-hour funding intervals provide more frequent adjustment opportunities compared to 8-hour CEX cycles. However, liquidity may be more limited during extreme market conditions, and the dependence on frontend partners adds complexity to position management."},{"question":"How reliable is Orderly Network's infrastructure for large AVAX positions?","answer":"Orderly's shared liquidity model provides better depth for large positions than typical DEX perpetuals, but remains less robust than major CEX platforms. The infrastructure is relatively new and dependent on multiple components including frontend partners and cross-chain bridges. Large position traders should consider splitting orders and monitoring frontend availability across different interfaces."}]}]
